WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.400
Hello everyone, I'm Carlos Scheidegger and I am going to tell you about next-generation

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:22.200
PDFs with Quarto & typst.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:35.919
I gave the title of my talk as Never Again in Outer Par Mode, and if you know what Outer

00:00:35.919 --> 00:00:38.560
Par Mode is, you know what this talk is about.

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:41.860
If not, let me tell you.

00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:45.560
So you're writing Quarto, you've heard this week, it's excellent, we love it.

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:50.279
I'm a full-time developer on Quarto, I'm biased, but I really think it's quite good and we

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:54.240
try really hard to make it even better, so if it's not good for you, we want to hear

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:55.840
about it.

00:00:55.840 --> 00:01:00.900
So you write your report, it's excellent, you're so ready to share it with the world,

00:01:00.900 --> 00:01:04.000
and you need to mail it to someone, so it needs to be a PDF.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.720
So you write your file and you go and hit render, or you call Quarto render, and we'll

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:14.980
go, yes, we'll render it for you, it's PDF, we'll use LaTeX, which is the way to create

00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:17.800
beautiful PDF files.

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:24.120
And then it says it's updating its Pack Live Manager, but you didn't ask to update it.

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:31.120
It's telling you, I don't want any new packages, I want my report.

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:34.519
And then it just says, it failed.

00:01:34.519 --> 00:01:38.860
And the reason it failed is, it's not in Outer Par Mode.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:44.519
And if you've ever used Quarto and PDF, unfortunately, I think you've seen this before, because it

00:01:44.519 --> 00:01:48.879
comes up all the time, and it's just a horrible error message.

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:52.320
So you look at it, it's like, what do I do now?

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:55.720
It's not in Outer Par Mode, let's go look at this.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:01:59.800
See the LaTeX manual, or the LaTeX companion for explanation, or press H for help.

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:04.320
Turns out, you get that even not in an interactive prompt, you can't press H, it's just on a

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:05.879
file somewhere.

00:02:05.879 --> 00:02:09.279
And then it says, okay, let's go look at the index.log for more information, because it's

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:10.279
an error.

00:02:10.279 --> 00:02:13.199
Great, they told me about the error, let's go look at it.

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:18.000
It's 50,000 characters of error messages.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.240
But okay, maybe it's there, so you go look at the file, and you're just like, okay, okay,

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:24.240
okay.

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:32.399
No, no, I'm going back to bed, I'll try this tomorrow, this is not going to be good.

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:34.399
And this happens all the time.

00:02:34.399 --> 00:02:37.839
This is a true story, I didn't know whether I wanted to give this talk with this title,

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:40.520
because I thought, it doesn't come up that often.

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:44.279
It recently has come up three separate times for me.

00:02:44.279 --> 00:02:47.520
Recently means since Saturday.

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:51.199
Since getting here at the conference, where I'm not developing quarto, three separate

00:02:51.199 --> 00:02:52.720
times I ran into this.

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:57.880
So no, never again in outer part mode, let's not do that.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:02.119
By the way, I used LaTeX for 20 years, I used to be an academic before I joined, I counted,

00:03:02.119 --> 00:03:08.360
I wrote more than 100 papers in LaTeX, and this trips me up still.

00:03:08.360 --> 00:03:12.679
I hope we don't have to sort of inflict on you this pain anymore.

00:03:12.679 --> 00:03:15.080
I want us to solve this problem so bad.

00:03:15.080 --> 00:03:18.880
LaTeX is beautiful, it was a groundbreaking system, it is still the way to generate the

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:23.240
most beautiful PDF documents you can, but I think there's an alternative now, and this

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:25.919
is what I want to tell you about.

00:03:25.919 --> 00:03:31.360
So if you're ready for coffee, there's a fantastic talk coming up after mine, but if you want

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:35.039
to sort of go back and then come back for the next talk, here's what I'm going to tell

00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:36.039
you about.

00:03:36.119 --> 00:03:43.080
Typed is a new system that quarto uses that lets you do PDF files.

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:47.880
I really hope it displaces LaTeX, you're going to see why, it's awesome.

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:52.119
You can download it today, it's available in 1.4 pre-releases, but we're still going

00:03:52.119 --> 00:03:55.880
to support LaTeX forever, so if you must use LaTeX, don't despair, we're not throwing it

00:03:55.880 --> 00:03:58.759
away, we're keeping it here.

00:03:58.759 --> 00:04:02.399
It's a little bit of extra work because it's so new, but I'll show you where the sharp

00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:03.679
edges are.

00:04:03.679 --> 00:04:06.399
So what's Typedst?

00:04:06.399 --> 00:04:11.000
The first thing is it's a weird way to pronounce it, but it's on their website.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
I used to say typist, maybe we can convince them to change, but it's Typedst.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.920
It's a new system for making PDF documents, and if you go to their website, they say that

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:25.399
it's for rocket scientists, but it's for the rest of us, too, which is great.

00:04:25.399 --> 00:04:29.880
And what they say is it views your changes instantly, it provides clear and understandable

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:35.239
error messages, it has a consistent styling system, and it uses familiar programming constructs.

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:39.959
I want to tell you about all of that, because that's all true, and it's really great.

00:04:39.959 --> 00:04:42.420
So I hope we can convince you to do that.

00:04:42.420 --> 00:04:48.200
So Quarto meets Typedst.

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:51.160
What do you have to do to get Typedst working?

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:54.299
Hopefully you don't have to do anything.

00:04:54.299 --> 00:04:59.119
If this is your Quarto document, with your YAML front matter, your title, your author,

00:04:59.119 --> 00:05:06.839
and your format, it might just be a matter of switching from format PDF to format Typedst.

00:05:06.839 --> 00:05:12.119
If you're okay with a sort of standard formatted document, this works today, and you're going

00:05:12.119 --> 00:05:14.119
to get a PDF document.

00:05:14.119 --> 00:05:20.720
The advantage of that is you do not need to install TinyTek, it is bundled with Quarto,

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:23.720
and it is much faster than LaTeX.

00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:29.040
So hopefully you might not have to do anything, but I'll show you what else you get if you

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:31.640
actually want to go to the next step.

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:33.239
So I'm going to give you four quick demos today.

00:05:33.239 --> 00:05:36.760
I'm going to show you how to make academic posters with Quarto.

00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:40.040
I don't know if Lisa is in the audience.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:44.839
To tell you how easy this is, I had three tiny demos to show you today, and then Lisa

00:05:44.839 --> 00:05:48.799
told me that we really need academic posters in Quarto.

00:05:48.799 --> 00:05:53.440
And we knew there was a template for Typedst, and so I was like, I think we can do this.

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:58.160
And we set it up last night in the hotel before the talk today.

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:02.760
You can go check my GitHub repository for this talk, and you will see.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:05.600
I'm going to show you how the errors are nice.

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:10.600
I'm going to show you this really fantastic feature about how it handles fonts.

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:15.459
And I'm going to show you a really cool, completely new design for documents that just really

00:06:15.459 --> 00:06:18.440
showcases the power of Typedst.

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:22.320
So let's start with posters.

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:24.880
And here.

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:30.920
So here is a demo.

00:06:30.920 --> 00:06:35.720
So I'm using VS Code, which apparently, according to Nick, makes me a maniac of some kind.

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:37.320
I apologize.

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:38.839
I'm used to it.

00:06:38.839 --> 00:06:40.820
This is a Quarto document.

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:42.160
It's just marked down.

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:47.959
If you have format equals HTML and you ask it to render, we'll fire up a preview.

00:06:47.959 --> 00:06:48.959
We will run it.

00:06:48.959 --> 00:06:54.279
And you will get a preview just like you would for any website.

00:06:54.279 --> 00:06:56.320
So you get that.

00:06:56.320 --> 00:06:58.720
It's not an academic poster, but it's your content.

00:06:58.720 --> 00:06:59.720
There's some figures.

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:03.079
There's lists, tables, equations, images, and so on and so forth.

00:07:03.079 --> 00:07:08.760
So let's say that you needed to do an academic poster as of last night.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:15.160
If you switch your format from there to Typedst, you see that you have to do things a little

00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:16.160
bit different.

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:19.079
We're going to fix this in about 24 more hours.

00:07:19.079 --> 00:07:20.760
I just didn't have time to do that.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:22.640
We'll be using all of the metadata from Quarto.

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:23.640
We're not right now.

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:24.640
So it's not perfect.

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:25.640
Let's try again.

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:28.440
We tell it, please preview.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:33.440
And we're going to make a new poster.

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:36.440
And now you get a poster.

00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:37.440
Okay.

00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:43.279
So that's kind of cool.

00:07:43.279 --> 00:07:46.160
I wasn't sure whether or not people were going to use it.

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:51.239
And then this morning, someone pinged me on Mastodon saying, hey, I made a CRAN poster

00:07:51.239 --> 00:07:52.239
with this.

00:07:52.239 --> 00:07:53.239
And it worked.

00:07:53.239 --> 00:07:54.839
So there's at least one person that made it work.

00:07:54.839 --> 00:07:57.799
So trust me, this is easy.

00:07:57.799 --> 00:08:00.359
You can see the formatting is a little bit different, right?

00:08:00.359 --> 00:08:02.440
The tables are rendered a little bit differently.

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:05.720
The code blocks are rendered not quite the same, but they're pretty close.

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:08.079
And we're working to make it as close as possible.

00:08:08.079 --> 00:08:09.079
You get equations.

00:08:09.079 --> 00:08:10.200
You get lists.

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:13.399
You get other kinds of things that I hope to show you.

00:08:13.399 --> 00:08:18.079
So for example, here is a block of text that has a different color behind it.

00:08:18.079 --> 00:08:24.859
So this is my first opportunity to show you a little bit about how types actually looks

00:08:24.859 --> 00:08:25.859
like in code.

00:08:25.859 --> 00:08:29.720
Because I want to show you that this is actually really kind of simple.

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:31.880
So here's a raw code block for types.

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:36.640
So in Quarto, if you want to do something that's format specific, you use these raw

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:39.599
blocks to get the code to do what you want.

00:08:39.599 --> 00:08:45.320
And so if you want a block that the background is this light gray that is inside eight points

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:48.359
from the margin, and it has a radius of four, you start a block.

00:08:48.359 --> 00:08:51.760
This is the way that you call a command from types.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:56.000
You put your markdown code inside, including markdown things like lists.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.500
And then you just close your block here, right?

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:02.440
So there's an even easier way to do this with using divs from Pandoc, but I just wanted

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:06.299
to show you sort of what this looks like if you were to sort of have to do the fancy sort

00:09:06.299 --> 00:09:09.440
of pure type thing.

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:11.400
I don't know if you've ever had to do this in LaTeX.

00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:17.760
I promise you, this one is so much cleaner and easier to work than that.

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:22.799
And it will give you a reason to do that.

00:09:22.799 --> 00:09:28.479
Let's say that if you happened to type that instead of RGB, because you thought that that's

00:09:28.479 --> 00:09:31.000
how callers worked, right?

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:35.039
Well, they don't work exactly like that.

00:09:35.039 --> 00:09:38.880
But this gives me a chance to show you error messages.

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:43.280
So I'm running the dev version of Quarto, so I want to know exactly where the error

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:44.280
came.

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:45.280
You won't see this.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:51.119
You are going to see this part right here, where it's saying compiler poster error.

00:09:51.119 --> 00:09:59.159
I expected a caller or none, but I found a string right here.

00:09:59.159 --> 00:10:02.640
Compare that to not in outer par mode.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.359
What error did I make that it says not in outer par mode?

00:10:05.359 --> 00:10:06.760
It's got nothing to do with my code.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:11.559
When typist makes an error, it tells you what the error is, and it said it was expecting

00:10:11.559 --> 00:10:15.280
a caller, and you gave it a string, and it points you exactly in the source where that

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:16.400
is.

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:19.760
And it does that very consistently, and it's some of the best error messages that I've

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:20.760
ever seen.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:25.159
And I spent six months working in Quarto error messages, so I care about them.

00:10:25.159 --> 00:10:29.400
These folks have done a fantastic job of their own, so I'm happy to show you that we can

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:32.280
actually then guide you to do the right thing.

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:37.559
So error messages and types are just really nice.

00:10:37.559 --> 00:10:39.119
Let me tell you about fonts.

00:10:39.119 --> 00:10:44.159
So if you've ever used PDF LaTeX from way back then, font support is not great.

00:10:44.159 --> 00:10:45.400
There's no Unicode support.

00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:49.159
It's very hard to figure out if your code is going to render the way that you want.

00:10:49.159 --> 00:10:52.479
It's just generally a mess.

00:10:52.479 --> 00:10:56.400
Lua LaTeX and ZLaTeX do a little bit better, but still, the system itself doesn't know

00:10:56.400 --> 00:11:00.419
a lot about fonts, and so it's hard for it to reason about what's possible.

00:11:00.419 --> 00:11:03.380
So let me start with a very basic demo here.

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:10.059
So we, again, are going to show this, and I'm going to tell you.

00:11:10.059 --> 00:11:11.900
Here is font support, right?

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:18.020
So again, I'm starting with a raw block here that says set the text to be of a particular

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:19.020
font.

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:21.859
But notice I'm using two fonts and not one.

00:11:21.859 --> 00:11:25.979
The other thing I'm doing is I'm putting a fenced div around that statement.

00:11:25.979 --> 00:11:31.299
And the reason I'm doing that is to show you that naturally, typist will keep its state

00:11:31.299 --> 00:11:32.859
to the blocks around it.

00:11:32.859 --> 00:11:36.820
So this just happens by natural sort of way in which types work, which is not how LaTeX

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:37.820
work.

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:40.659
And you have to remember, does this one work in the current environment?

00:11:40.659 --> 00:11:42.059
Does this work set for the entire document?

00:11:42.059 --> 00:11:43.380
Am I going to get it wrong?

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:45.260
In types, everything is scoped.

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:48.059
If you want to keep your changes to something, you just put a block around it, and everything

00:11:48.059 --> 00:11:50.419
just works.

00:11:50.419 --> 00:11:52.260
So here is my text.

00:11:52.260 --> 00:11:53.260
Let's render it.

00:11:53.539 --> 00:11:59.659
It's going to do the same thing as before.

00:11:59.659 --> 00:12:10.140
And now what's neat about this one is if you like avatar, you get your papyrus font.

00:12:10.140 --> 00:12:13.700
But it didn't get the papyrus font for the second one.

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:17.419
Because the papyrus font does not have the Arabic glyphs for that.

00:12:17.419 --> 00:12:21.340
So it detects it, and it says, hey, I cannot possibly render for that one.

00:12:21.419 --> 00:12:28.059
So let me try the next font you gave me, which is the Arabic font from Google, and it renders

00:12:28.059 --> 00:12:29.059
it.

00:12:29.059 --> 00:12:32.299
And not only does it render it, I unfortunately do not know how to read Arabic.

00:12:32.299 --> 00:12:36.780
But ligatures in Arabic text are extremely important, because they actually change the

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:37.780
meaning of the word.

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:38.780
So they're not very readable.

00:12:38.780 --> 00:12:42.119
And so in old PDF, this is very hard to do in types.

00:12:42.119 --> 00:12:46.440
You just get that for free, and these are rendered properly if the font supports it.

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:48.739
So this is something that's kind of impossible to do in LaTeX.

00:12:48.739 --> 00:12:50.140
You just get it for free in types.

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:52.020
It's really nice.

00:12:52.020 --> 00:12:58.940
So last quick demo for something completely different.

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:02.179
What if you are running a small department, like an institution, and you want to have

00:13:02.179 --> 00:13:05.219
a newsletter for your college somewhere?

00:13:05.219 --> 00:13:06.219
This is a newsletter.

00:13:06.219 --> 00:13:09.940
I just want to show you how it's possible to do something that looks completely different,

00:13:09.940 --> 00:13:13.260
that almost looks like it was typeset with something like Illustrator or something of

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:14.260
that sort.

00:13:14.260 --> 00:13:19.140
It's just another format, and this is what it looks like.

00:13:19.140 --> 00:13:20.460
There we go.

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:21.979
So you have two columns.

00:13:21.979 --> 00:13:24.820
You can put sort of code on one column or code on the other.

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:27.460
You have links and so on, and you still have your code.

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:32.659
So you can line things just like you would in your sort of R Markdown quarto inline code.

00:13:32.659 --> 00:13:33.979
They're just there.

00:13:33.979 --> 00:13:37.979
You can do sort of fancy treatments for these and cross-references, and they all work.

00:13:37.979 --> 00:13:43.039
And the content for this looks like your Markdown, and it's semantic.

00:13:43.039 --> 00:13:45.900
If you want to, say, put something on the sidebar that's an article, you just make a

00:13:45.900 --> 00:13:51.299
fence div that says article, and then the template is going to put there.

00:13:51.299 --> 00:13:54.700
The reason I'm sharing this with you is I want to show you something real quick that

00:13:54.700 --> 00:14:01.039
might have escaped notice, just to show you how incredible types is as understanding graphics.

00:14:01.039 --> 00:14:04.619
Look at this part right here, where it says award-winning science.

00:14:04.619 --> 00:14:07.739
Pay attention to this line here.

00:14:07.739 --> 00:14:08.739
Looks very innocuous, right?

00:14:08.739 --> 00:14:10.340
It's just a line there.

00:14:10.340 --> 00:14:12.140
It's a little sus, right?

00:14:12.140 --> 00:14:14.700
Like it knows how to end exactly at the right spot.

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:16.659
Is that a coincidence?

00:14:16.659 --> 00:14:18.739
What's going on there, right?

00:14:18.739 --> 00:14:23.099
You know, if you're in a different place, maybe you don't do award-winning science.

00:14:23.099 --> 00:14:24.739
You do okay science.

00:14:24.739 --> 00:14:25.739
It's okay.

00:14:25.739 --> 00:14:28.219
It's fine.

00:14:28.219 --> 00:14:33.099
But if you want a kick-ass newsletter, we got you.

00:14:33.099 --> 00:14:36.299
And now pay attention to this.

00:14:36.299 --> 00:14:39.340
Look at where the line went.

00:14:39.340 --> 00:14:44.700
So types knows how to reason about font sizes right on the language.

00:14:44.700 --> 00:14:48.460
So if you want to do things like I want to take this thing and I want to stretch it so

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:52.580
that it fits exactly at the right spot, or if this text is too big, I want it to render

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:56.900
with a different font, you can all do this from a real programming language with scope,

00:14:56.900 --> 00:14:59.380
with variables, with error messages.

00:14:59.380 --> 00:15:02.900
So if you're a template user, this is so much better than LaTeX.

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:04.460
I cannot tell you.

00:15:04.460 --> 00:15:08.619
If you've written any LaTeX template, you're thinking this is impossibly good.

00:15:08.619 --> 00:15:11.299
I promise it's very, very easy.

00:15:11.299 --> 00:15:14.460
And I will show you how easy it is.

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:16.580
Where is the template for the department news?

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:18.380
It's right there.

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:19.900
And this just looks like code.

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:21.460
It's incredible.

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:23.380
So let's close the other ones.

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:27.500
I'm almost done with my talk, I promise.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:36.460
The way this works is literally you just ask for the size of the content and then you use

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:40.260
You align it to whatever is left.

00:15:40.260 --> 00:15:44.219
You measure the image, you find the correct line width, and then you subtract it from

00:15:44.219 --> 00:15:45.219
the other one.

00:15:45.219 --> 00:15:47.919
So right in your code, you just literally say how big was this text that I was going

00:15:47.919 --> 00:15:48.919
to render?

00:15:48.919 --> 00:15:49.919
It's this much.

00:15:49.919 --> 00:15:50.919
Make the line.

00:15:50.919 --> 00:15:51.919
That's all that one.

00:15:51.919 --> 00:15:57.500
It's a real programming language operating on text with full right-to-left support, ligature

00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:59.940
support, computation, all of that.

00:15:59.940 --> 00:16:00.940
Great error messages.

00:16:00.940 --> 00:16:03.099
It's very easy to write.

00:16:03.099 --> 00:16:04.859
You can kind of see what it's doing.

00:16:04.859 --> 00:16:05.859
It's not complicated.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:07.580
So I'm going to do two columns.

00:16:07.580 --> 00:16:08.619
Here's the first column.

00:16:08.619 --> 00:16:09.619
Here's the other column.

00:16:09.619 --> 00:16:11.020
It's right there.

00:16:11.020 --> 00:16:13.700
It's actually incredibly clean and well-designed.

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:20.700
So I hope this gets you excited to actually put sort of, you know, try it out.

00:16:20.700 --> 00:16:22.179
It's actually much better than I thought.

00:16:22.179 --> 00:16:26.140
I was, okay, that's not great.

00:16:26.140 --> 00:16:28.140
What happened there?

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:29.700
Hello?

00:16:29.700 --> 00:16:33.140
This is what happens with live demos.

00:16:33.140 --> 00:16:34.140
I apologize.

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:35.140
There we go.

00:16:35.419 --> 00:16:38.219
And we were here, but I'm done with my talk.

00:16:38.219 --> 00:16:42.739
So here's SharpAddress before we're done.

00:16:42.739 --> 00:16:46.820
Rich just presented, and Rich is the table master of the universe, if you don't know.

00:16:46.820 --> 00:16:51.340
Like, GT is just mind-blowingly good, and it pains me to tell you that we don't get

00:16:51.340 --> 00:16:53.260
GT support in types right now.

00:16:53.260 --> 00:16:55.219
But we're going to work on it.

00:16:55.219 --> 00:16:56.219
It's possible.

00:16:56.219 --> 00:16:57.219
It's just not there yet.

00:16:57.219 --> 00:16:58.500
So some features are not there.

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:00.260
We have callouts in Quarto.

00:17:00.260 --> 00:17:01.260
They don't quite work.

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:04.180
They sort of render, but they're kind of not great.

00:17:04.939 --> 00:17:07.780
So types has existed for about a year and a half.

00:17:07.780 --> 00:17:08.819
So it's very new.

00:17:08.819 --> 00:17:11.739
There's a lot of support out there already, but it's a little early.

00:17:11.739 --> 00:17:16.219
So you're probably going to have to do something, but we want to help you.

00:17:16.219 --> 00:17:20.979
So if this excites you as sort of an alternative for doing PDFs, that is not LaTeX, has better

00:17:20.979 --> 00:17:27.180
messages, it's kind of great, please give it a try and let us know what you find.

00:17:27.180 --> 00:17:28.180
So that's it.

00:17:28.180 --> 00:17:32.180
If you want to find more, we have documentation, links to this slide and the talks.

00:17:33.180 --> 00:17:35.180
Happy to take questions.

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:39.180
Thank you.

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:42.180
There are a couple of questions.

00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:45.180
First one is the obvious question.

00:17:45.180 --> 00:17:47.180
So how about equations?

00:17:47.180 --> 00:17:49.180
Is it decent enough to replace LaTeX?

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:52.180
So there's a demo of equations right on the poster.

00:17:52.180 --> 00:17:57.180
So you can see it's very good, but it's not as good as LaTeX is right now.

00:17:57.180 --> 00:18:02.180
So you might have to do a little bit of digging, but extending it is quite simple.

00:18:02.180 --> 00:18:04.180
And they're getting better sort of every day.

00:18:04.180 --> 00:18:07.180
They do a new release every two, three weeks, and they all improve equations.

00:18:07.180 --> 00:18:10.180
So it will be there in probably three months or so.

00:18:10.180 --> 00:18:13.180
I'd say it's 90% there, but it's not 100%.

00:18:14.180 --> 00:18:15.180
Second question.

00:18:15.180 --> 00:18:17.180
Will short codes work with types?

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:18.180
Yes.

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:23.180
If your short code emits just regular markdown, which most do, they will work with types.

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:27.180
It's just another quarto feature that just should work well together, yes.

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:30.180
We should have tested the icons, Richard.

00:18:30.180 --> 00:18:31.180
I didn't realize it.

00:18:31.180 --> 00:18:33.180
But we'll make sure it works by tonight.

00:18:33.180 --> 00:18:34.180
Okay.

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:37.180
Next question.

00:18:37.180 --> 00:18:45.180
What would it take to develop the document in types and then convert it to LaTeX to submit it to a journal, for example?

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:52.180
What I would recommend you do is, so if you go on the repository that I had there linked,

00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:57.180
I have a document that was a paper I published as an academic that I converted to QMD.

00:18:57.180 --> 00:19:01.180
And I have it sort of compiling from quarto to LaTeX and to types.

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:03.180
And that's the easiest way to do it.

00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:07.180
But if you are having a hard time, you can try to use something like Melissa suggested earlier,

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:12.180
which is Pandoc will parse from the output back into the input if you want to try that.

00:19:12.180 --> 00:19:16.180
So I haven't tested it for types, but that's sort of something you can try to do.

00:19:16.180 --> 00:19:19.180
So you take the types output, convert it to LaTeX, and then you go.

00:19:19.180 --> 00:19:23.180
I think you should just use quarto markdown for it and target both of those because that's nice.

00:19:23.180 --> 00:19:26.180
But there might be a way to do the fancy way out.

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.180
Okay, last question.

00:19:29.180 --> 00:19:32.180
Does types support other output formats than PDF?

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:33.180
Not yet.

00:19:33.180 --> 00:19:36.180
They said that they are going to support HTML, but it's not out yet.

00:19:36.180 --> 00:19:42.180
So right now they're used as a PDF engine in the same way that we use LaTeX only as a PDF engine,

00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:44.180
even though you can get more things out of LaTeX as well.

00:19:45.180 --> 00:19:46.180
Thank you.

